{
	"nodes": [
		{
			"id": "64d9ebf4024246c7",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 0,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 2510,
			"height": 2170,
			"label": "Reading Mathematics"
		},
		{
			"id": "ac4345faddf84091",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Reading math is different**\n\nMathematics is read non-linearly: experts constantly double-back. Eye-tracking shows experts focus on exposition while students fixate on formulas. Learning to read math is the first skill.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9e7d9f88520940a4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is a definition?**\n\nA mathematical definition gives a complete, precise description of a word — unlike English, there is no room for intuition or ambiguity. Example: \"an integer n is even if there exists m such that n = 2m.\"",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3f17157092064ba4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Definitions vs intuition**\n\nUsing intuition instead of the verbatim definition causes errors. Example: \"Is 0 even?\" — the definition resolves this immediately (0 = 2·0). \"How many holes in a straw?\" — depends on which definition of \"hole\" you use. Always return to the definition.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "6b6a5a4b5f54495e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Theorems and friends**\n\nMathematical results come in several flavours: lemma (stepping stone), proposition (interesting but intermediate), theorem (major result), corollary (immediate consequence). These are guidelines — history is full of misnomers.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "42e6a4e678964fc4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Working with a definition**\n\nWhen you encounter a new definition, immediately try to find examples and non-examples. Sample diverse cases: positive, negative, zero, large, small, edge cases. Pattern-hunting builds intuition grounded in the definition.",
			"x": 880,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "f179ab9c2588427f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Hypothesis and conclusion**\n\nEvery mathematical result has two parts: the hypothesis (what must be true to apply the result) and the conclusion (what is guaranteed). You must verify the hypothesis before invoking the conclusion.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "1e9d42ee26c84fe9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Mathematical results are infallible**\n\nUnlike empirical sciences, a correctly proven mathematical result is objectively true — no counterexamples, no interpretation. This is what makes mathematics unique among academic fields.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "7d2b2ebf18574f47",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Define odd and prime numbers**\n\nWrite precise definitions of \"odd number\" and \"prime number.\" Multiple correct answers exist.",
			"x": 880,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5de20ea583114ae9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisibility examples**\n\nGiven \"a divides b if there exists n such that b = na\": give three pairs where a|b and three where a∤b.",
			"x": 1270,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a7b594276c0a4149",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is a proof?**\n\nA proof is a sequence of statements starting from the hypothesis, ending with the conclusion, where each line follows logically from previous lines. If all statements are objectively true, the theorem is established.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "16812c4caed242ad",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Identify hypothesis and conclusion**\n\nFor each of four mathematical statements (square roots, unique multiplicative identity, infinitely many primes, Archimedean property), identify the hypothesis and conclusion.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d9c7e652cbe3432b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Palindromic number hypothesis and conclusion**\n\nIdentify the hypothesis and conclusion in: \"Any 4-digit palindromic number is divisible by 11.\"",
			"x": 880,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "2b62834657c54c66",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] State a result about quirky numbers**\n\nState a mathematical result you believe is true about quirky numbers (n is quirky if n² is not even). Clearly label the hypothesis and conclusion.",
			"x": 1270,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "2734aeb348f840cf",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Hypothesis and conclusion for slippery statements**\n\nFor four statements about slippery numbers, identify the hypothesis and conclusion of each.",
			"x": 1660,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "fae1ff96382848ab",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Slippery numbers**\n\nA positive integer b is slippery if 3|b but 2∤b. Find the first five slippery numbers.",
			"x": 2050,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b3874aab55c14844",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Anatomy of a proof**\n\nA proof unpacks definitions, performs logical deductions, and reassembles the pieces to reach the conclusion. Proofs are primarily text — not collections of equations. The tombstone □ marks the end.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "573dd531419e4e2a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Self-explanation training**\n\nAfter each line of a proof: identify the main idea, explain it in terms of earlier ideas (from the proof, prior theorems, or your own knowledge), and check whether your explanation resolves any questions. This is self-explanation — research shows it significantly improves proof comprehension.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ffb87651a0d547ef",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Are slippery statements true or false?**\n\nDetermine whether each of the four slippery-number statements is true or false. Prove or give a counterexample.",
			"x": 880,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "eefc3af45b0c4c87",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Generality in proofs**\n\nWorking with an arbitrary object (not a specific one) lets a single argument cover infinitely many cases. \"Let a and b be even integers\" proves the result for all even integers, not just particular ones.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 1680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "49d4c082275e4e51",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proving vs applying a theorem**\n\nWhen proving, you assume the hypothesis and show the conclusion. When applying, you verify the hypothesis holds in your situation and then invoke the conclusion. These are opposite directions.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 1680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "18cd3988f6fa413c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Self-explanation vs paraphrasing and monitoring**\n\nParaphrasing just restates in different words. Monitoring just says \"I understand.\" Neither adds understanding. Self-explanation connects the line to prior knowledge and the proof's logical structure.",
			"x": 880,
			"y": 1680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "eb6af0968e514dbe",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] SET on a palindromic number proof**\n\nApply self-explanation training to the proof that any 4-digit palindromic number abba = 11(91a + 10b) is divisible by 11.",
			"x": 1270,
			"y": 1680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "e1c8b2a254794d4c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] SET on a triangular-number proof**\n\nApply self-explanation training to the proof that T_{n-1} + T_n = n², which uses a clever rearrangement of two sums.",
			"x": 1660,
			"y": 1680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "fe9fb570eb9e4bb7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Even-digit palindromes divisible by 11**\n\nProve that any palindromic number with an even number of digits is divisible by 11.",
			"x": 100,
			"y": 1930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ddaa4e273d8046c6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Restate and prove the product proposition**\n\nThe proof of \"product of two evens is even\" only used one factor being even. Restate the proposition with a weaker hypothesis and prove it.",
			"x": 490,
			"y": 1930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f2b69192798d4120",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 2610,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 4850,
			"height": 1480,
			"label": "Quantifiers and Implications"
		},
		{
			"id": "4179942e1a30464e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The existential quantifier**\n\n∃x ∈ S, P(x) means at least one element of S makes P true. To prove it, find a single witness — one concrete example suffices. Mnemonic: backwards E for \"Exists.\"",
			"x": 2710,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "63060b7cf5bd4308",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Math vs English: OR**\n\nMathematical OR is inclusive (both true counts). English OR is usually exclusive (\"pizza or Thai\" implies not both). Always use the mathematical definition when doing logic.",
			"x": 3100,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "0f52b414736d4453",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The universal quantifier**\n\n∀x ∈ S, P(x) means P holds for every element of S. To prove it, work with an arbitrary x — if it works for an unspecified element, it works for all. Mnemonic: upside-down A for \"All.\"",
			"x": 3490,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8d0bc24e9fc448e0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Doubly quantified statements**\n\nSame-type quantifiers can be swapped freely: ∀x∀y = ∀y∀x. But mixing types changes meaning: ∀x∃y ≠ ∃y∀x. The universal quantifier confers a \"scope\" — the existential choice may depend on the universally quantified variable.",
			"x": 2710,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a2f42cdfbf2f4ff1",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Negating the universal quantifier**\n\n¬(∀x, P(x)) = ∃x, ¬P(x). \"Not every horse is black\" means \"there exists a non-black horse.\" To disprove a ∀ statement, find one counterexample.",
			"x": 3100,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "323e3c9c7592423c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proving quantified statements**\n\nTo prove ∀x, P(x): let x be arbitrary, show P(x). To prove ∃x, P(x): exhibit one specific x. These are fundamentally different proof strategies — universal needs generality, existential needs a witness.",
			"x": 3490,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "86aebf2bde3e402d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Quantifiers turn predicates into propositions**\n\nA predicate P(x) has no truth value on its own. Attaching a quantifier (∀x or ∃x over a set) produces a proposition — a statement that is unambiguously true or false.",
			"x": 3880,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "dd4f35c877a243db",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is an implication?**\n\nP ⟹ Q means \"if P then Q.\" It is false only when P is true and Q is false. The bottom two rows of the truth table are vacuous truths: a false hypothesis implies anything.",
			"x": 4270,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "38a230a7185542f4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Contrapositive of an implication**\n\nThe contrapositive of P ⟹ Q is ¬Q ⟹ ¬P. Unlike the converse, the contrapositive IS logically equivalent to the original — they have identical truth tables. This gives a powerful proof technique.",
			"x": 2710,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ca1c37ddb3da4530",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Converse of an implication**\n\nThe converse of P ⟹ Q is Q ⟹ P. The converse of a true statement is NOT necessarily true: \"all dogs are animals\" is true, but \"all animals are dogs\" is false.",
			"x": 3100,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a27a6de953bb499c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Math vs English: NOT**\n\nIn English, \"not everything is alright\" and \"everything is not alright\" sound the same. In math, ¬(∀x, A(x)) = ∃x, ¬A(x) vs ∀x, ¬A(x) — very different meanings. Placement of negation matters. Shakespeare got it wrong.",
			"x": 3490,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a5b8f2658eab436f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Negating an implication**\n\n¬(P ⟹ Q) = P ∧ ¬Q. A counterexample to P ⟹ Q is an x where P(x) is true but Q(x) is false. Counterexamples are exactly how implications are disproved.",
			"x": 3880,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3903849257554f9f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Negating the existential quantifier**\n\n¬(∃x, P(x)) = ∀x, ¬P(x). \"There is no pink horse\" means \"every horse is not pink.\" To disprove an ∃ statement, show it fails for all elements.",
			"x": 4270,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2479f4d3355d439c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Quantifier order matters**\n\n\"Every real number has a negative\" (∀x∃y, x+y=0) is true. \"There is a number that is the negative of every real number\" (∃y∀x, x+y=0) is false. Swapping ∀ and ∃ changes meaning drastically. The second demands a single y that works for all x.",
			"x": 4660,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "733cc88c206d41e4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Vacuous truth**\n\nWhen the hypothesis P is false, P ⟹ Q is automatically true regardless of Q. \"If pigs can fly, then the sky is black\" is true. Vacuous truths appear frequently in mathematics whenever conditions are never met.",
			"x": 5050,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "db7b7c866bc44d41",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Evaluate a quantified statement**\n\nIs ∀x ∈ ℝ, ∃y ∈ ℝ, y² = x true? Describe it in plain English without variable names.",
			"x": 5440,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5bd283ac2a0a4284",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Is implication associative?**\n\nDetermine whether P ⟹ (Q ⟹ R) and (P ⟹ Q) ⟹ R are logically equivalent by constructing truth tables.",
			"x": 5830,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7228762ae6e442bd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Polynomial quantifier statements**\n\nDetermine truth of six statements about polynomials with various ∀/∃ combinations: ∀x∀p p(x)=0, ∀x∃p p(x)=0, etc. Prove or give counterexamples.",
			"x": 6220,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9ff684cd34ca4360",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Quantifier-implication equivalence**\n\nDetermine whether [∀x, P(x)] ⟹ [∀x, Q(x)] and ∀x, [P(x) ⟹ Q(x)] are logically equivalent.",
			"x": 6610,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "25d8525eae4f43ee",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Translate sentences to quantifier notation**\n\nConvert five English sentences (about cows, horses, sports, textbooks, real numbers) into formal quantifier notation using predicates.",
			"x": 7000,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "84d6140ddccd4d2d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] If and only if**\n\nP ⟺ Q means both P ⟹ Q and Q ⟹ P. The two statements are logically equivalent — they share the same truth value in every case. Proving iff requires two separate proofs, one per direction.",
			"x": 2710,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "73b6cb21ea1d4b19",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Math vs English: implication**\n\nEnglish if-then is often secretly iff: \"if you do the dishes, you can go out\" implies the converse too. Also, English implications are typically causal; mathematical ones need not be. \"If it rains, an asteroid hits Jupiter\" can be true.",
			"x": 3100,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "cf4a83d7ffc045f3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proof by contrapositive**\n\nTo prove P ⟹ Q, you may equivalently prove ¬Q ⟹ ¬P. Example: \"if n² is even then n is even\" is proved by showing \"if n is odd then n² is odd.\"",
			"x": 3490,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d44ebe1677024274",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Birthday quantifier statements**\n\nFor S = students in a classroom and B(a,b) = \"same birthday\", translate four ∀/∃ combinations into plain English.",
			"x": 3880,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "45e8624781444884",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Write contrapositive and converse**\n\nFor four statements (x²+y²=4, product of rationals, divisible by 2, pass the course), write the contrapositive and converse.",
			"x": 4270,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d2284e30b877491e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove contrapositive equivalence by truth table**\n\nConstruct the truth table for ¬Q ⟹ ¬P and verify it matches P ⟹ Q.",
			"x": 4660,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9f95dac5f8e343f9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Find a predicate where quantifier swap matters**\n\nFind a predicate P such that ∀x∃y P(x,y) and ∃x∀y P(x,y) differ in truth value.",
			"x": 5050,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "1a7537da97514b23",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Negate complex logical statements**\n\nNegate four statements with mixed quantifiers and implications, including ∀x[P(x) ⟹ Q(x)], ∃x[P(x) ⟺ Q(x)], etc.",
			"x": 5440,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5ebd21bc71ae47e8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Negate the definition of continuity**\n\nNegate the five-quantifier ε-δ definition of continuity: ∀c∈ℝ, ∃L∈ℝ, ∀ε>0, ∃δ>0, ∀x∈ℝ, |x−c|<δ ⟹ |f(x)−L|<ε. Each quantifier flips and the implication becomes a conjunction.",
			"x": 5830,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "03b39aa1255b48e8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove negation of implication by truth table**\n\nShow ¬(P ⟹ Q) = P ∧ ¬Q by constructing truth tables for both sides.",
			"x": 6220,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "09a206d726a842fc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Negate quantified sentences**\n\nWrite three propositions (square negative, cubed roots, smallest positive real) using quantifiers, then negate each.",
			"x": 6610,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f943614e39924dad",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Translate logical statements to English**\n\nConvert three formal quantified statements into plain English, avoiding variable names and negation as much as possible.",
			"x": 7000,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "38bd0d0e79694833",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Necessary and sufficient conditions**\n\n\"P is sufficient for Q\" means P ⟹ Q (P is enough). \"P is necessary for Q\" means Q ⟹ P (you can't have Q without P). \"P is necessary and sufficient for Q\" means P ⟺ Q.",
			"x": 2710,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "7f775e6736024948",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] n is even iff n² is even**\n\nProve both directions: n even ⟹ n² even (direct) and n² even ⟹ n even (contrapositive). Conclude: n odd iff n² odd.",
			"x": 3100,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c9a1512c14474362",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Implication truth tables**\n\nBuild truth tables for P ⟺ Q, P ⟹ (Q ∨ ¬P), and P ⟹ (Q ⟺ ¬R).",
			"x": 3490,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c483005ffe0f47b2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Negate the prime characterization**\n\nNegate the deeply nested ∀∃ statement characterizing primes: ∀p ∈ ℤ⁺, [p ∈ ℙ ⟺ (∀a∀b, (∃k, pk=ab) ⟹ ∃ℓ[pℓ=a ∨ pℓ=b])].",
			"x": 3880,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0c8188388d1f4bed",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 7560,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 4460,
			"height": 2730,
			"label": "Sets and Propositions"
		},
		{
			"id": "859208fd793f4225",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 7610,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 4360,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Sets"
		},
		{
			"id": "969b9834ce734817",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is a set?**\n\nA set is an unordered collection of well-defined, distinct objects. Elements are either in or not in — no ambiguity. The empty set ∅ contains nothing. \"Well-defined\" means membership is unambiguous.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2a8be864fb9c4100",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cartesian product**\n\nA × B is the set of all ordered pairs (a,b) where a ∈ A, b ∈ B. Unlike sets themselves, pairs are ordered: (a,b) ≠ (b,a) in general, so A × B ≠ B × A in general.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "0bd9af8f0af140a7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Set-builder notation**\n\nWhen a set is too large or infinite to list, describe it by a property: {x : x satisfies P}. This is unambiguous and concise. It also lets us define sets we could never list, like \"all people with brown hair.\"",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d800078c5e634cbd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Set notation**\n\nSets are written with braces: {a, b, c}. We use ∈ for membership and ∉ for non-membership. Sets ignore order and duplicates: {1,2,2,3,3,3} = {3,1,2}. A set of sets is NOT the same as the union of its members.",
			"x": 8440,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "b520936d23ea4539",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Subsets**\n\nS ⊆ T means every element of S is also in T. A subset need not be strictly smaller — every set is a subset of itself. The empty set is a subset of every set.",
			"x": 8830,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "5c49d778653b4b13",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Union and intersection**\n\nS ∪ T collects elements in either set (the \"or\" operation on sets). S ∩ T collects elements in both (the \"and\" operation). Venn diagrams visualize these operations.",
			"x": 9220,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "519048839f26440d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Set difference**\n\nS \\ T consists of elements in S that are not in T. Unlike union and intersection, set difference is NOT symmetric: S \\ T ≠ T \\ S in general.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "440b95eeb8d24273",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Set equality via double inclusion**\n\nTwo sets are equal when S ⊆ T and T ⊆ S. This double-inclusion strategy is how we *prove* two sets are the same — show every element of each is in the other.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a959f11f7e004e71",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Sets can contain anything**\n\nElements of a set can be numbers, symbols, words, functions, or even other sets. A set containing sets (like {{1,2},{3}}) is different from the set {1,2,3}.",
			"x": 8440,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8661b93b88324fcd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Standard number sets**\n\nThe key sets: ℤ⁺ = {1,2,3,...}, ℤ* = {0,1,2,...}, ℤ (integers), ℚ (rationals), ℝ (reals). The convention ℕ is ambiguous (does it include 0?), so we use ℤ⁺ and ℤ* to avoid confusion.",
			"x": 8830,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "c864790053a9463b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Cartesian product properties**\n\nFor A = {♣, ♥} and B = {↑, ↓}: What is A × ∅? Is A × B = B × A? Is (A × B) × A = A × (B × A)?",
			"x": 9220,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d7d5dcd5df0a4b86",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Expand a set in set-builder notation**\n\nThe set S = {z : z = x+y, x ∈ {1,2}, y ∈ {5,7}} is finite. Explicitly write out all elements of S.",
			"x": 9610,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3c30c63f926543d3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute set operations**\n\nFor S = even integers and T = non-negative integers, compute S ∩ T, S \\ T, and T \\ S in set-builder notation.",
			"x": 10000,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f74e0dad602d4232",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Subset and intersection**\n\nWhich is true: A ⊆ A ∩ B, or A ∩ B ⊆ A? Prove your answer.",
			"x": 10390,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "614203c4e6024b17",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove subset relationships**\n\nFor A = {n ∈ ℤ : n = 8x+3y} and B = {n ∈ ℤ : n = 5x+3y}, show A ⊆ B. Is B ⊆ A?",
			"x": 10780,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3bab72383ba84da4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Which sets are equal?**\n\nCompare A={1,2,2,3,3,3}, B={3,1,2}, C={{1,2},{3}}. Which are equal? Remember sets ignore duplicates and order, but a set of sets is different.",
			"x": 11170,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5c6fe3d4ce6f46ed",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Write sets explicitly**\n\nFour sets given in set-builder or structural notation. Explicitly write out all their elements. Includes power sets and Cartesian product constructions.",
			"x": 11560,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "da8a5fcfc08f4882",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Complement of a set**\n\nGiven a universe U, the complement Aᶜ = {x ∈ U : x ∉ A} is everything in U not in A. The complement depends on the choice of universe — it's really a special case of set difference: Aᶜ = U \\ A.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "76cb156d2e714b44",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove set equality**\n\nShow that A = {n ∈ ℤ* : n = 4k+1} and B = {n ∈ ℤ* : n = 4k−3} are equal using double inclusion.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "82c220cbd8524f85",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Subset implies union equality**\n\nShow that if A ⊆ B then A ∪ B = B.",
			"x": 8440,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "015d80deec42446f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Complement in ℤ**\n\nWith universe U = ℤ, find Sᶜ and Tᶜ where S = even integers and T = non-negative integers.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "548e3c119a1445d7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove set identities**\n\nProve five set identities: A ∩ Aᶜ = ∅, A \\ B = A ∩ Bᶜ, distributivity of ∪ over ∩, difference over union, and products over intersection.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a4cdfa8087d04605",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 7610,
			"y": 1400,
			"width": 2020,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Propositional Logic"
		},
		{
			"id": "5f0903d4edf445ca",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is a proposition?**\n\nA proposition is a statement that is unambiguously true or false. \"Your mother has green hair\" is a proposition (albeit false). \"How many shirts do you own?\" is neither — it can't be true or false. Propositions need not be true; they must be decidable.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 1490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "09d04c165f59432a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Conjunction and disjunction**\n\nP ∧ Q (AND / conjunction) is true only when both are true. P ∨ Q (OR / disjunction) is true when at least one is true. Mathematical OR is inclusive — both being true counts.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "aa9473ddcdd24a89",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Predicates**\n\nA predicate is a statement with a variable: P(x) = \"x has green hair.\" Its truth depends on what you plug in. Substituting a value turns a predicate into a proposition.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3b937a1a496b46e9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Negation**\n\n¬P flips truth values: true becomes false, false becomes true. Negation is the simplest logical connective — it acts on a single proposition.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "62448581485a4277",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Truth tables**\n\nA truth table lists every combination of truth values for component propositions and computes the result for the compound statement. Two statements with identical truth tables are logically equivalent (written P = Q).",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "074fa0883a3848f9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Classify propositions, predicates, neither**\n\nFor seven sentences (including \"Today is Friday\", \"x² > π\", etc.), classify each as a proposition, predicate, or neither.",
			"x": 8440,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "92cf9c1bc54e42ac",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Evaluate compound propositions**\n\nGiven predicates P(S) and Q(S) on subsets of ℤ, and specific sets A and B, determine the truth of ¬P(B), P(A)∨Q(A), Q(A)∧Q(B), ¬(P(A)∧Q(B)), etc.",
			"x": 8830,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9a15b32da3624d02",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Predicate-satisfying subsets**\n\nGiven A = {−2,−1,0,1,2} and three predicates P, Q, R on subsets of A, explicitly list all subsets S satisfying P(S) ∧ Q(S) ∧ ¬R(S).",
			"x": 9220,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a747a60812ba4961",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] De Morgan's laws**\n\n¬(P ∧ Q) = ¬P ∨ ¬Q and ¬(P ∨ Q) = ¬P ∧ ¬Q. Negation flips AND ↔ OR and negates each part. These can be proved by truth tables.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "14a275086a4447eb",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Build a compound truth table**\n\nConstruct the truth table for (¬P ∨ Q) ∧ R.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "da44ddf700254401",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Construct truth tables**\n\nBuild truth tables for four compound statements involving three propositions P, Q, R.",
			"x": 8440,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d1d3ded97bd14714",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Identify logical equivalences**\n\nFrom the truth tables constructed in the previous exercise, determine which statements are logically equivalent.",
			"x": 7660,
			"y": 2490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a56f3356a7f441b9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Negate a disjunction (De Morgan's)**\n\nConjecture what ¬(P ∨ Q) simplifies to, then prove your conjecture using a truth table.",
			"x": 8050,
			"y": 2490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "1567d569dfc64de0",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 12120,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 2120,
			"height": 4660,
			"label": "Relations"
		},
		{
			"id": "0d19ef2eeba7487f",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 12170,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 850,
			"height": 1530,
			"label": "Binary Relations"
		},
		{
			"id": "e1e7a25ac90c4d45",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is a binary relation?**\n\nA relation R between sets A and B is a subset S_R ⊆ A × B. We write aRb when (a,b) ∈ S_R. Relations formalize any notion of comparison: equality, ordering, divisibility, proximity.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a90f18ad5781486f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Relations on a set**\n\nWhen B = A, a relation is a subset of A × A. Familiar examples on the same set: = is {(a,a) : a ∈ A}, < is {(a,b) : a < b}, ≤ is {(a,b) : a ≤ b}. Any comparison between elements of A is a relation.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "5edc45199e0c4895",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Reflexive, irreflexive, symmetric, anti-symmetric**\n\nReflexive: aRa always. Irreflexive: never aRa. Symmetric: aRb ⟹ bRa. Anti-symmetric: aRb and bRa ⟹ a=b. These four properties classify the basic behaviour of a relation. Symmetry and anti-symmetry are not negations of each other.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ff41af60608e4f87",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Equality relation as a subset**\n\nFor an arbitrary non-empty set A, what subset S ⊆ A × A defines the equality relation \"=\"?",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "243ef91921054528",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Transitive, total, left-total, functional**\n\nTransitive: aRb and bRc ⟹ aRc. Total: any two distinct elements are comparable. Left-total: every a relates to some b. Functional: each a relates to at most one b. Left-total + functional will define functions.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "4067656717924774",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Checking relation properties**\n\nTo verify a property: prove it for all relevant elements. To disprove: find one counterexample. Example: ab > 1 on ℝ⁺ is symmetric (ab = ba) but not reflexive (0.5 · 0.5 = 0.25 < 1).",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "b2cc383433494634",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Check left-total and functional**\n\nVerify that a specific relation between A = {2,4,6} and B = {♦, ♠} is left-total and functional.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "66031a0433e641c9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisibility relation properties**\n\nDefine aRb if a|b on ℤ. Determine whether R is reflexive, (anti-)symmetric, transitive, or total.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "cc77b7a3f091428b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Determine relation properties**\n\nSeven relations on various sets. For each, check reflexive, irreflexive, symmetric, anti-symmetric, transitive, total.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "e5a36006d19a4156",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 12170,
			"y": 1650,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 840,
			"label": "Equivalence Relations"
		},
		{
			"id": "310b8ac7a13546ca",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is an equivalence relation?**\n\nA relation that is reflexive, transitive, and symmetric. Named after equality, which satisfies all three. Captures \"morally equal\" — two things interchangeable for a given purpose. Example: a ∼ b if b − a = 2πk for some integer k.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "395dcf0f7c444bb3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Equivalence classes**\n\nGiven ≅ on A, the equivalence class [a] = {x ∈ A : x ≅ a}. All elements related to a are collected into one class. The quotient A/≅ is the set of all classes. Example: [0] under mod-2π consists of integer multiples of 2π.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3c2eae5357df4ece",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Equivalence relation on pairs**\n\nShow (a,b) ∼ (c,d) iff a+d = b+c is an equivalence relation on ℤ⁺ × ℤ⁺. Check reflexive, symmetric, transitive.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "40899a219b2349c0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Sign equivalence relation**\n\nDefine a ∼ b if sgn(a) = sgn(b). Show ∼ is an equivalence relation. How many equivalence classes does it create?",
			"x": 13000,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "71cfcaa5fcdb4a80",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Equivalence relations partition a set**\n\nEvery element belongs to exactly one equivalence class. Classes are either identical or completely disjoint — they never partially overlap. An equivalence relation perfectly splits A into non-overlapping pieces.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "67bf116f46464976",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Constructing the rationals**\n\nDefine (a,b) ∼ (c,d) iff ad = bc on ℤ × ℤ⁺. Show equivalence, give elements of [(1,2)], show addition and multiplication of classes are well-defined. Recognize: we've constructed ℚ.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b89ea14e9c684242",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Equivalence class properties**\n\nProve three properties: (i) a ∈ [a], (ii) [a] = [b] iff a ≅ b, (iii) [a] ∩ [b] = ∅ iff a ≇ b.",
			"x": 13000,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "671a859b917d4e75",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Which relations are equivalence relations?**\n\nFrom the seven relations in the previous exercise, identify which are equivalence relations.",
			"x": 13390,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b1e7aefb9b3f49b6",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 12170,
			"y": 2520,
			"width": 2020,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Order Relations"
		},
		{
			"id": "5c3865e07a4742d1",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] What is an order relation?**\n\nWeak order: reflexive + transitive + anti-symmetric (like ≤). Strong order: irreflexive + transitive + anti-symmetric (like <). Total order: every pair comparable. Partial order: some pairs may be incomparable.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 2610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8044882174714ef3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Partially ordered sets (posets)**\n\nA set A with a partial order R is a poset (A, R). Example: subsets of X ordered by ⊆ — not every pair is comparable ({1,2} and {2,3} are incomparable). Posets generalize the number line's ordering to settings with incomparability.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "39af984fcd9a4db9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Maximal and minimal elements**\n\nIn a poset, a is maximal if a ≤ x ⟹ a = x (nothing above a). Minimal: x ≤ a ⟹ x = a (nothing below a). A poset can have multiple maximal elements. Example: 6, 10, 15 are all maximal in a divisibility poset.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3833d57186284cfb",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Upper and lower bounds**\n\nM is an upper bound of S ⊆ A if x ≤ M for all x ∈ S. m is a lower bound if m ≤ x for all x ∈ S. A subset can have many bounds, or none. Upper bounds need not be in S itself.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "309990bd775042ba",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Which relations are order relations?**\n\nFrom the seven relations in the properties exercise, identify which are order relations (weak or strong, partial or total).",
			"x": 13000,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "79271d171a924231",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Maximum vs maximal**\n\nThe maximum M satisfies x ≤ M for ALL x — above everything. A maximal element just has nothing above it but need not be comparable to everything. A poset can have multiple maximal elements but at most one maximum.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 3360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2300f7af612b4676",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Supremum and infimum**\n\nSupremum = least upper bound: an upper bound M such that M ≤ U for every other upper bound U. Infimum = greatest lower bound. These are critical in analysis and calculus (least upper bound property of ℝ).",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 3360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a76576148a04473f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Find maximal elements**\n\nProve 10 and 15 are maximal in the divisibility poset on {1,2,3,5,6,10,15}.",
			"x": 13000,
			"y": 3360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "75a2ce163e164c19",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Find minimal elements**\n\nFind the minimal elements of the divisibility poset on {1,2,3,5,6,10,15}.",
			"x": 13390,
			"y": 3360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "90998e40ccd84f14",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Upper bound properties**\n\nProve 72 is the least upper bound of {8,12,36} in the divisibility order on ℤ⁺, and that multiples of upper bounds are upper bounds.",
			"x": 13780,
			"y": 3360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4ca88677f05d48a1",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisor-closed subsets poset**\n\nEnumerate divisor-closed subsets of {1,2,3,4,5,6,12}, order by inclusion, find maximal/minimal elements, and compute sup and inf for a specific pair.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 3610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4e4c49b294cd4bf9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Show no maximum exists**\n\nShow the divisibility poset has no maximum. What is the smallest number you could add to create one?",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 3610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0fa6f37ed0184ff7",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 12170,
			"y": 3830,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 780,
			"label": "Proof Techniques"
		},
		{
			"id": "83e8b0f4331d4e71",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proof by contradiction**\n\nAssume ¬T and derive R ∧ ¬R (a contradiction). Since R ∧ ¬R is always false, ¬T must be false, so T is true. Truth table confirms T and (¬T ⟹ R ∧ ¬R) are logically equivalent.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 3920,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "c3dcc838c11640de",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Contradiction is not constructive**\n\nA contradiction proof proves something exists or is true without revealing which case holds. Example: some digit of π occurs infinitely often, but the proof doesn't say which one. This is an open problem.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 4170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "46ebc5511c824cda",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The irrationality of √2**\n\nClassic contradiction: assume √2 = p/q in lowest terms, derive p² = 2q² so p is even, then q² = 2k² so q is even — contradicting lowest terms. Uses \"n² even ⟹ n even\" from contrapositive.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 4170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9bf9925db8dc488c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] A ∩ (B \\ A) = ∅**\n\nShow that A ∩ (B \\\\ A) = ∅ by contradiction.",
			"x": 13000,
			"y": 4170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "81f6c28bcbee4964",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] No smallest positive real number**\n\nProve by contradiction that there is no smallest positive real number. (Hint: halve a candidate.)",
			"x": 13390,
			"y": 4170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5df8ec471242411f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Contradiction proofs**\n\nThree proofs by contradiction: (a) if x+y irrational then x or y irrational, (b) prime > 2 is odd, (c) √p irrational for prime p.",
			"x": 12220,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a1dd4b5576e34142",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] No rational solution to x³+x²=1**\n\nShow x³+x²=1 has no rational solution. Set x = a/b, argue about parity of a and b to reach a contradiction.",
			"x": 12610,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9f3cae957b264e54",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 14340,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 4070,
			"height": 5170,
			"label": "Functions"
		},
		{
			"id": "ed7bb2c369ec4086",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 14390,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 3970,
			"height": 1720,
			"label": "Functions I"
		},
		{
			"id": "eced936aefc748db",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] A function is a special relation**\n\nA function f: A → B is a left-total, functional binary relation on A × B. Left-total: every input has an output. Functional: each input maps to exactly one output (the vertical line test).",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "b6b4c9fd45734255",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Function notation and data**\n\nWe write f: A → B, x ↦ f(x). The data of a function: name, domain A, codomain B, and the rule. The graph Γ(f) = {(a,f(a))} is exactly the relation subset. In practice, we think of functions as machines that eat inputs and produce outputs.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "add8c3e8877c4897",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Does a relation define a function?**\n\nGiven A ⊆ B, does S_g = A × A ⊆ A × B define a function? Check left-total and functional.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9ee9a69cf3b5423f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Domain, codomain, and range**\n\nDomain: where inputs live. Codomain: where outputs are allowed to live. Range (= image of the domain): where outputs actually land. Codomain ≠ range in general — the codomain may be larger.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2e455c72430148ed",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] When are functions equal?**\n\nTwo functions are equal when they share the same domain, same codomain, and the same output for every input. Changing the codomain (even if outputs match) creates a different function.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "0c9c3dc418a54c9c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Image of a set**\n\nf(U) = {f(x) : x ∈ U} for U ⊆ A. The image collects all outputs reachable from U. Computing images often requires double-inclusion proofs. Example: f(x) = x², f([-1,2]) = [0,4].",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9beae3cb12ba4046",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Injective (one-to-one) functions**\n\nf is injective if f(s₁) = f(s₂) ⟹ s₁ = s₂. Every output comes from at most one input. In the arrow picture: each element of B has at most one arrow pointing to it.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8a4b0a558f204f88",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Surjective (onto) functions**\n\nf is surjective if every element of B is hit: ∀t ∈ B, ∃s ∈ A, f(s) = t. In the arrow picture: every element in B has at least one arrow. Surjectivity depends on the codomain choice.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ecc72068fb1d4483",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Functions with empty domain or codomain**\n\nIs there a function f: ∅ → X? Is there a function g: X → ∅? Think about what left-total and functional mean in each case.",
			"x": 15610,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "20b585695c1e4196",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Which functions are equal?**\n\nCompare f: {0,1} → ℝ (x ↦ x), g: {0,1} → ℝ (x ↦ x²), and h: {0,1} → {0,1} (x ↦ x). Which are equal?",
			"x": 16000,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "aa25d73fdf2046d1",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Bijective functions**\n\nf is bijective = injective + surjective. Every element of B has exactly one arrow. Bijections are the \"perfect matchings\" between sets. Compositions of bijections are bijections.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8ec164a562564eac",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Composition preserves injectivity**\n\nIf f: B → C and g: A → B are both injective, then f ∘ g is injective. Proof chains: f(g(x₁)) = f(g(x₂)) ⟹ g(x₁) = g(x₂) ⟹ x₁ = x₂.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a704c801dd71483c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Composition preserves surjectivity**\n\nIf f: B → C and g: A → B are both surjective, then f ∘ g is surjective. For any c ∈ C, find b with f(b) = c, then find a with g(a) = b, so f(g(a)) = c.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "b8413f8657d140b8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Preimage of a set**\n\nf⁻¹(V) = {x ∈ A : f(x) ∈ V} for V ⊆ B. The preimage collects all inputs that land in V. Despite the f⁻¹ notation, this does NOT require an inverse function to exist.",
			"x": 15610,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "bc528f9c932b402e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proving and disproving injectivity**\n\nTo prove: assume f(x₁) = f(x₂), deduce x₁ = x₂. To disprove: find two distinct inputs with the same output. Domain matters — x² is injective on (0,∞) but not on ℝ.",
			"x": 16000,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "4dfbfc27fa4b4778",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Proving and disproving surjectivity**\n\nTo prove: let t ∈ B be arbitrary, construct s ∈ A with f(s) = t. To disprove: find one element of B not in the range. Surjectivity proofs use the existential quantifier pattern.",
			"x": 16390,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "e528e9d19bfb4afa",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute image of a sphere**\n\nFor p(x,y,z) = (x,y) (projection), find p(S) where S is the unit sphere x² + y² + z² = 1.",
			"x": 16780,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9d340e5d43c544fa",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Image of intersection is subset**\n\nShow f(U₁ ∩ U₂) ⊆ f(U₁) ∩ f(U₂). Give an explicit counterexample showing equality doesn't hold in general.",
			"x": 17170,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4276f302d1e84b8e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Image of union is equality**\n\nShow f(U₁ ∪ U₂) = f(U₁) ∪ f(U₂).",
			"x": 17560,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b68a5e3831284ac6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Strictly increasing implies injective**\n\nA function f: ℝ → ℝ is strictly increasing if f(x) < f(y) whenever x < y. Show strictly increasing ⟹ injective.",
			"x": 17950,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b7718439f93247bd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Binary strings and functions**\n\nShow there is a bijection between infinite binary strings B = {0110100...} and the set N = {f: ℤ⁺ → {0,1}}.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "db9d3c8b0ad94ed3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Classify injective/surjective**\n\nFour functions (sin, diagonal map, projection, polynomial evaluation at 0): determine injective, surjective, both, or neither.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f727002af1a54df3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Composition and injectivity**\n\nIf f ∘ g is injective, must g be injective? Must f be injective? Prove or give counterexamples.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "6d1a0736e6c14fff",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Composition and surjectivity**\n\nIf f ∘ g is surjective, which of f or g must be surjective? Prove your result.",
			"x": 15610,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "385d2404f2714f39",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute a preimage**\n\nFor f(x) = x² on ℝ, find f⁻¹((-1,1)).",
			"x": 16000,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7c41b72f1f61461c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute images and preimages**\n\nThree problems: sin image/preimage on [-2π,2π], g(x,y)=xy images, h(x)=(x³,x²) preimage of [-1,1]².",
			"x": 16390,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "feb17f665a3c49c7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Product of functions and injectivity**\n\nDefine h(a) = (f(a), g(a)). Show that if f or g is injective, then h is injective. Is the converse true?",
			"x": 16780,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "db6748f91b4d4837",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Which functions are bijective?**\n\nRevisit the functions from earlier exercises. Which are bijective?",
			"x": 17170,
			"y": 1430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ae3d276147eb4f19",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Injective, surjective, or neither?**\n\nFour functions: |x|, min(x,y), (xy,y³), Thomae's function. Classify each as injective, surjective, both, or neither.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 1620,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "460519b89e8246a7",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 14390,
			"y": 1840,
			"width": 2020,
			"height": 3280,
			"label": "Functions II"
		},
		{
			"id": "ed1a8a29e9fd4d4c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Binary operators and identity elements**\n\nA binary operator takes two things and returns one (e.g. +, ×). The identity for an operator is the element that does nothing: 0 for addition, 1 for multiplication.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 1930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3cafcb07fd094b46",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Inverse with respect to an operator**\n\nGiven an operator with identity id, the inverse of x is the element y such that x op y = id. Additive inverse of 2 is -2. Multiplicative inverse of 2 is 1/2. Not every element need have an inverse (0 has no multiplicative inverse).",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 2180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "182b73ad04524dee",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Function composition**\n\n(f compose g)(x) = f(g(x)). Composition is itself a binary operator on functions. The identity function id(x) = x is the identity element for composition.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 2430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9b80e9f16edb4677",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Inverse functions**\n\nThe inverse of f: A to B is g: B to A such that f compose g = id_B and g compose f = id_A. Not every function has one. When it exists f is invertible and we write f inverse.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 2680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8b7eed81fe59436a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Invertibility requires bijectivity**\n\nA function is invertible iff it is bijective. Non-surjective means some output has no preimage so g cannot be defined there. Non-injective means two inputs share an output so g cannot be functional.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 2930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "bb1a849fc92747c0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Find or disprove inverse functions**\n\nThree functions: f(x,y)=(2x,x-y), g(n)=10^{n+1}+1, h(n)=smallest prime >= n. Determine invertibility.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 2930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "6af688690ee14935",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Left- and right-invertible functions**\n\nShow left-invertible iff injective, right-invertible iff surjective.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 2930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3df720e3f40f41aa",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] One-sided inverses**\n\nFind sets A,B and f: A to B such that (a) f compose g = id but g compose f != id, (b) vice versa.",
			"x": 15610,
			"y": 2930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "2fa5a2868e6f4604",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cardinality of a set**\n\nThe cardinality |S| measures how many elements. For finite sets this is counting. For infinite sets we use injections: |S| <= |T| if there is an injection S to T.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 3180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9da83eb5845e4b2b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Determine invertibility**\n\nFive functions: rational indicator, x^3, (x-1)/(x+1), piecewise n/2 or (n-1)/2, sum-of-parts. Determine invertibility.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 3180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7cc5ea4b77394f09",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove invertible iff bijective**\n\nProve the forward direction: if f is invertible then f is bijective.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 3180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0c5a278c52ce479c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Equal cardinality via bijection**\n\n|S| = |T| if there is a bijection S to T. |S| < |T| if there is an injection but no surjection. This extends counting to infinite sets where subsets can have the same cardinality as the whole.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 3430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "32d5b74c64a9449b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Subset cardinality**\n\nShow that if S is a subset of T then |S| <= |T|.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 3430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "bf5036a2b45a40c7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Countable sets**\n\nA set S is countable if |S| <= |N| (injection S to N). Countably infinite means |S| = |N|. Key tool: a countable union of pairwise disjoint countable sets is countable.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 3680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "bbd6958b1db2433a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Infinite sets can match their subsets**\n\n|N| = |2N| via n maps to 2n. Unlike finite sets, an infinite set can be in bijection with a proper subset. This is the first surprise of infinite cardinality.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 3680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "95659b47e45d4eb8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Construct explicit bijections**\n\nFour pairs: Z- and Z+, Q and Q union {pi,sqrt2}, dyadic rationals and Q, [0,1) and (0,1). Construct explicit bijections.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 3680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "03684044981e43b3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The integers are countable**\n\n|Z| = |N|. Map n to (|n|, sgn(n)+1) into N x N which is countable. Since N is a subset of Z gives |N| <= |Z|, both inequalities yield equality.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 3930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "5ed1be92b0094cf2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Power set**\n\nP(S) is the set of all subsets of S, also written 2^S. For finite S with n elements, |P(S)| = 2^n.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 3930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "27dd1b5d25cc4157",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Algebraic numbers are countable**\n\nShow the set of algebraic numbers is countable. Use: polynomials have finitely many roots and Q[x] is countable.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 3930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "e669381932a2487b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |N x N| = |N|**\n\nShow that N x N is countable.",
			"x": 15610,
			"y": 3930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b0ec6b48cc254a05",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |(0,1)| = |R|**\n\nConstruct an explicit bijection between (0,1) and R.",
			"x": 16000,
			"y": 3930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9bf9e851d1c1421e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cantor's theorem**\n\n|S| < |P(S)| for any set S. The injection x maps to {x} shows <=. Diagonalization shows no surjection: D = {x in S : x not in f(x)} cannot be in the image. Generalizes uncountability of R.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 4180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a9861dea40c54ffd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The rationals are countable**\n\n|Q| = |N|. Map p/q in lowest terms to (p,q) in Z x Z+ which is countable. Despite appearing much larger, Q has the same cardinality as N.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 4180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "eb7684de006e483c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] There is no set of all sets**\n\nIf V were the set of all sets, P(V) subset V, contradicting |V| < |P(V)|. The collection of all sets is a proper class, not a set. Proper classes escape Cantor comparison.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 4430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "df5b7c6e8cad4421",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The reals are uncountable**\n\n|R| > |N|. Cantor diagonal argument: list all reals in [0,1], construct a new real differing in the n-th digit from the n-th listed. This real is not in the list -- contradiction.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 4430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ef27d1c98c3e4b15",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Advanced cardinality**\n\nFour problems: irrationals same as R, finite subsets of Z+ countable, Q[x] countable, {f: Z+ to {0,1}} same as R.",
			"x": 15220,
			"y": 4430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "601924bd3784465e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cantor-Schroder-Bernstein theorem**\n\nIf there are injections f: A to B and g: B to A, then there exists a bijection h: A to B, so |A| = |B|. Not obvious -- the proof is non-trivial and omitted.",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 4680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "731826ff05c24127",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Why diagonalization fails for Q**\n\nEvery natural number is encoded in finite data. Real numbers generally need infinite data (infinite decimal expansions). The diagonal argument exploits this infinite bandwidth gap.",
			"x": 14830,
			"y": 4680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "13ed77b79d574924",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |(a,b)| = |R| and |[a,b]|?**\n\nGeneralize: show |(a,b)| = |R| for any a < b. What about [a,b]?",
			"x": 14440,
			"y": 4930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "bb6ea5377b5448a4",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18510,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 1730,
			"height": 8850,
			"label": "Number Theory"
		},
		{
			"id": "fea1a0aab3144ef0",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18560,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 850,
			"height": 780,
			"label": "Divisibility"
		},
		{
			"id": "94ef3d42ec584bad",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Divisibility definition**\n\nDefinition of b|a: there exists k∈Z with a=bk. Notation b|a means \"b divides a\" and b∤a means \"b does not divide a\". Examples: 4|12, 5∤12, k|(k²+k).",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "84e6e4aca28e4ff4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Basic divisibility properties**\n\nFive properties: (i) transitivity, (ii) a|b,a|c⟹a|(mb+nc), (iii) a|b,a|(b+c)⟹a|c, (iv) a|b,b|a⟹a=±b, (v) b≠0,a|b⟹|a|≤|b|. Proofs of (i) and (ii) given.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "11e7367bf06b47cc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisibility and zero**\n\nFor what values of n is n|0? For what values of n is 0|n?",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "91d37d286a8448b8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisibility with products**\n\nTwo proofs: (a) if ac|bc and c≠0 then a|b; (b) if a|b and c|d then ac|bd.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "a3f738fb57314c8f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove divisibility properties (iii)–(v)**\n\nProve divisibility properties (iii)-(v): subtraction, antisymmetry, and size bound.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0053e080d7d54486",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18560,
			"y": 900,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 2030,
			"label": "GCD and Euclidean Algorithm"
		},
		{
			"id": "461f657350314f5c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Well-Ordering Principle**\n\nEvery non-empty subset of Z⁺ has a least element. Taken as an axiom that extends to Z*. Fails for Z: the set of all integers has no minimum.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "831533874d614ebe",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Division Algorithm**\n\nFor a,b∈Z with b>0, there exist unique q,r∈Z with a=qb+r and 0≤r<b. Proof uses Well-Ordering Principle. q is quotient and r is remainder.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 1240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "100e74a75f7e46ef",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Case analysis via remainders**\n\nTechnique: Division Algorithm splits Z into b residue classes. Example: show 3|(n³-n) by checking n=3q, 3q+1, 3q+2. Useful when direct proof is hard.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 1490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "168978792e20435b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] GCD definition and coprimality**\n\ngcd(a,b) = max{d∈Z: d|a and d|b}. Convention gcd(0,0)=0. Coprime/relatively prime: gcd(a,b)=1. Every number divides 0 so gcd(a,0)=|a|.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 1490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "09ad5b15387f4a4b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] GCD respects remainders**\n\nIf a=bq+r then gcd(a,b)=gcd(b,r). Proof via common-divisor argument. Key insight: replace large numbers with smaller ones.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "1b286a7787ec4877",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute gcd(1053,481)**\n\nFind gcd(1053,481).",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9f70f4c0a4f946b4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Factor n³-n**\n\nFind a slick proof that 3|(n³-n) by factoring n³-n = n(n-1)(n+1).",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "68ddb79a27cf45f6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] 4|(n²-1) for odd n**\n\nShow 4|(n²-1) for any odd integer n.",
			"x": 19780,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "018cfcef174b4c47",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Euclidean Algorithm**\n\nRepeated division: remainders form a strictly decreasing sequence of positive integers, so must reach 0. Last nonzero remainder is gcd. Worked example: gcd(616,427)=7.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "18581038713d4887",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] GCD of a linear combination**\n\nShow that gcd(3a+2b, a+b) = gcd(a,b) for any a,b∈Z*. Hint: apply gcd-respects-remainders repeatedly.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "fb34e8dbfabd412a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Bézout's Identity**\n\nFor any a,b∈Z, there exist m,n∈Z with am+bn=gcd(a,b). Proof by Well-Ordering Principle: the smallest positive element of {ax+by} is the gcd.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "eb6ec35e23c84bb2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute four gcds**\n\nCompute gcd(a,b) for four pairs using the Euclidean Algorithm: (252,198), (385,595), (420,378), (4620,6930).",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "17a66ca1eda04f97",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Back-substitution technique**\n\nTechnique: unwind Euclidean algorithm steps to find Bézout coefficients m,n. Worked example: 616x+427y=7 by back-substituting through the EA steps.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 2490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a270388a1a1a48ce",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Bézout corollaries**\n\n(i) Every common divisor of a,b divides gcd(a,b). (ii) If d>0 is a common divisor and am+bn=d, then d=gcd(a,b).",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 2490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "684742f8d8f04383",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Existence of a modular inverse**\n\nLet n∈Z+ with n≥2. Show that for any a∈Z with gcd(a,n)=1, there exists b∈Z such that n|(ab-1).",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 2740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0b193734b36247c0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] GCD after dividing**\n\nShow gcd(a/d, b/d) = 1 where d = gcd(a,b).",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 2740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4a0edf3683794d79",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove Bézout corollaries**\n\nProve that every common divisor divides the gcd, and the characterization corollary.",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 2740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3bf516008cfb48e2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Solve Bézout equation**\n\nFind integer solution to 1053x+481y = gcd(1053,481).",
			"x": 19780,
			"y": 2740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4a1d58f0f4124976",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18560,
			"y": 2960,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 2470,
			"label": "Modular Arithmetic"
		},
		{
			"id": "e91ff61f7c884c37",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Congruence modulo n**\n\nDefinition: a≡b (mod n) if n|(b−a). Notation and basic examples. Introduces modular equivalence as a way of saying two integers have the same remainder when divided by n.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 3050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a3e54c69da6d475a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Congruence is an equivalence relation**\n\nProof that congruence mod n is reflexive (n|0), symmetric (n|(b−a) implies n|(a−b)), and transitive (adding divisibilities). This makes it a bona fide equivalence relation on Z.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 3300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "19943b5a1ba142e6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] a²−2 not divisible by 7 implies a−4 not divisible by 7**\n\nShow that if a²−2 is not divisible by 7, then a−4 is not divisible by 7. Approach: check all residues mod 7.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 3300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c705cb927f304094",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Arithmetic of congruences**\n\nIf a≡r (mod n) and b≡s (mod n), then (a+b)≡(r+s) (mod n) and ab≡rs (mod n). Proof by writing n|( r−a) and n|(s−b) and combining. This says addition and multiplication are well-defined on congruence classes.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 3550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d4c81625cbb748dc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Congruence classes and Z_n**\n\nThe congruence class [a]_n = {x ∈ Z : x ≡ a (mod n)}. There are exactly n classes: [0],[1],…,[n−1]. The set Z_n = Z/nZ is the collection of these classes. Addition and multiplication tables for Z_4 as a worked example.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 3800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ba2a0439c9bd4e40",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Last-digit computation**\n\nThe last digit of a number is its residue mod 10. Worked example: finding the last digit of 4^441 by repeatedly reducing mod 10. Demonstrates the power of modular arithmetic for computation.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 3800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "e20cb7ab6bad4f31",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Is exponentiation well-defined mod n?**\n\nDetermine whether exponentiation is well-defined in modular arithmetic: if a≡b (mod n) and c≡d (mod n), does a^c≡b^d (mod n)? Find a counterexample or prove it.",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 3800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "bdba7d86b1d84d07",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Digital roots formula**\n\nThe digital root r(n) is the single-digit number obtained by recursively summing digits (e.g., 15993→27→9). Show that r(n) = 1 + [(n−1) mod 9].",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 4050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7b5a072bab004773",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Last digits of large powers**\n\nFind the last digit of: (a) 7^100, (b) 3^1111, (c) 4^223, (d) 8^400. Use modular arithmetic mod 10, finding the cycle length for each base.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 4050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ee0884cc8bb2416f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] 9 divides 10^n − 1**\n\nShow that 9|(10^n − 1) for all n ∈ Z⁺. Observe that 10 ≡ 1 (mod 9), so 10^n ≡ 1 (mod 9).",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 4050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ccf490a693e441ec",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Squares are 0 or 1 mod 4**\n\nShow that for any n ∈ Z⁺, n² is congruent to either 0 or 1 mod 4. Check all four residue classes of n mod 4.",
			"x": 19780,
			"y": 4050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d9cc85e7544a448e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Modular cancellation lemma**\n\nIf gcd(p,x)=1 and mx≡nx (mod p), then m≡n (mod p). Proof: p|(m−n)x and coprimality gives p|(m−n). The coprimality condition is necessary: 3·2≡1·2 (mod 4) but 3≢1 (mod 4). When p is prime, we can cancel any x≢0 (mod p).",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 4240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "aff9a3e59bd14171",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Fermat's Little Theorem**\n\nIf p is prime and p∤a, then a^{p−1}≡1 (mod p). Proof: the set {0a,1a,…,(p−1)a} is a rearrangement of Z_p (by the cancellation lemma). Multiply all nonzero elements: (p−1)!·a^{p−1}≡(p−1)! (mod p), then cancel (p−1)!.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 4490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "fbbc5161fa4a4ddc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] a² ≡ b² mod p implies a ≡ ±b mod p**\n\n(a) Show that if p is prime and a²≡b² (mod p), then a≡b (mod p) or a≡−b (mod p). Hint: p|(a²−b²)=p|(a−b)(a+b), use the prime divisibility property. (b) Show this fails for composite p.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 4490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7649f7fd9ad84741",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Corollary: a^p ≡ a (mod p)**\n\nFor any integer a and prime p, a^p ≡ a (mod p). This removes the restriction p∤a from Fermat's Little Theorem — it holds for all integers, including multiples of p (both sides are 0 mod p).",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 4740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a48faae63250418c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove the FLT corollary**\n\nProve that a^p ≡ a (mod p) for any integer a and prime p, noting that the restriction p∤a from Fermat's Little Theorem is not present. Handle the case p|a separately.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 4740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "699adc1e98f64081",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Does 7 divide 3^2001 + 4^2001?**\n\nDetermine whether 7 | (3^2001 + 4^2001). Use Fermat's Little Theorem: 3^6 ≡ 1 (mod 7) and 4^6 ≡ 1 (mod 7), then reduce the exponent 2001 mod 6.",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 4740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "22ccc0bfee6b43f4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Multiplicative inverses in Z_p**\n\nIf p is prime, every nonzero element of Z_p has a multiplicative inverse: a^{−1} = a^{p−2} (mod p) by Fermat's Little Theorem. Alternative proof via Bézout: gcd(a,p)=1 gives am+pn=1, so am≡1 (mod p). Contrast with Z_4, where [2] has no inverse.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 4990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "4ad17e271c734ba8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Find the inverse of [22] in Z_41**\n\nCompute [22]^{−1} in Z_41. Two approaches: Fermat's Little Theorem (compute 22^39 mod 41) or the Euclidean algorithm (find m with 22m+41n=1).",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 5240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "2e3ff497e1b74e6e",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18560,
			"y": 5460,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 1530,
			"label": "Primes"
		},
		{
			"id": "a09588d851154c2c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Prime definition**\n\nA prime number is p>1 that cannot be written as a product of two smaller natural numbers. Classical definition avoids the ambiguity of allowing units or zero.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 5550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ec3b47d0e713485c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] FTA existence**\n\nEvery positive integer >1 can be written as a product of primes. Proof by contradiction + Well-Ordering Principle: if some integer can't be factored, the smallest such integer is composite — contradiction.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 5800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d8eec15303684a7b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Prime divisibility property**\n\np is prime iff for any a,b∈Z, p|ab implies p|a or p|b. Proof (⟹) uses gcd(a,p)=1 when p∤a, then coprime-divides-product. Definition in higher mathematics.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 6050,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "45c154f3a6c6412a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] FTA uniqueness**\n\nPrime factorization is unique up to reordering. Proof: given two factorizations p₁…pₙ=q₁…qₘ, the prime divisibility property forces p₁=qⱼ; cancel and repeat.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 6300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "b2ab5855c9a340fc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Primality is necessary**\n\nGive an example showing primality is necessary: p,a,b with p composite, p|ab, but p∤a and p∤b.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 6300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4f55a4e26cf44565",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] p|n iff p|n²**\n\nShow: if p is prime and n∈Z, then p|n if and only if p|n².",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 6300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "62b53944148b4b92",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prime property in logic**\n\nWrite the prime divisibility property (p|ab ⟹ p|a or p|b) using propositional logic notation.",
			"x": 19780,
			"y": 6300,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "65367abc62234ea9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Infinitely many primes**\n\nEuclid's proof: suppose only finitely many primes p₁,…,pₙ. Then x=p₁…pₙ+1 is not divisible by any pₖ, contradicting FTA.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 6550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "5b25d0045e034c74",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Irrationality via FTA**\n\nExample: log₃₆(105) is irrational. Proof: assume p/q, get 36^p = 105^q, compare prime factorizations — impossible since 2 appears on left but not right.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 6550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "6441a659374f43b2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Divisibility via prime factorization**\n\nThree parts: (a) show b|a iff each prime's exponent in b is ≤ that in a; (b) show gcd(a,b) = product of primes with min exponents; (c) compute gcd(9⁴·10², 12³).",
			"x": 19390,
			"y": 6550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "8d7e39fc7dd24a19",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Trailing zeros of 100!**\n\nDetermine how many zeros appear at the end of 100! = 100·99·…·1. Hint: count pairs of factors of 2 and 5 in the prime factorization.",
			"x": 19780,
			"y": 6550,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7dd6151b260546bf",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Counting divisors**\n\nThree parts: (a) find the number of positive divisors of 360; (b) show the general formula (d₁+1)(d₂+1)⋯(dₙ+1) for n=p₁^d₁⋯pₙ^dₙ; (c) give a necessary and sufficient condition on the dᵢ for n to be a perfect square.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 6800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "6181e54ad222444e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Infinitely many primes of the form 4k+3**\n\n(a) By imitating Euclid's proof, show there are infinitely many primes of the form 4k+3. (b) Show why the same argument fails for primes of the form 4k+1.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 6800,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9a757575f15d4a40",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 18560,
			"y": 7020,
			"width": 850,
			"height": 1780,
			"label": "Diophantine Equations"
		},
		{
			"id": "a654c78c298c49c3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Coprime divides product**\n\nIf a|bc and gcd(a,b)=1 then a|c. Proof via Bézout: write am+bn=1, multiply by c to get a(cm)+bc(n)=c, so a|c.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 7110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "bbeb8a50758a43b9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Linear Diophantine Equation**\n\nDefinition: ax+by=d where a,b,d∈Z and we seek integer solutions (x,y). Rational solutions always exist but integer solutions are more interesting and restrictive.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 7360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "127ef62aba7e40e0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove coprime divides product**\n\nProve: if a|bc and gcd(a,b)=1 then a|c.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 7360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7068698e9902482b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] LDE solvability criterion**\n\nax+by=c has integer solutions if and only if gcd(a,b)|c. Characterizes exactly which linear Diophantine equations are solvable.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 7610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "4607f8c87f3e4e61",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] LDE particular solution**\n\nFind one solution using Euclidean algorithm + back-substitution + scaling. Worked example: 504x+1155y=42. Key idea: solve 504x+1155y=21 first, then scale by 2.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 7860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "1ce0c06bedd34c5d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove LDE solvability**\n\nProve: ax+by=c is solvable iff gcd(a,b)|c.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 7860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "24c1cab372d8449e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] LDE general solution**\n\nIf (x₀,y₀) is one solution to ax+by=c with d=gcd(a,b), the general solution is x=x₀+n(b/d), y=y₀−n(a/d). Proof uses coprime-divides-product and gcd(a/d,b/d)=1.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 8110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2e129ccd9beb40db",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Solve LDE 1053x+481y=39**\n\nFind a solution to 1053x+481y=39.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 8110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "bc67f6682f654f97",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] LDE non-negative solutions**\n\nConstrain n to get x≥0, y≥0. May have finitely many or no non-negative solutions. Example: 504x+1155y=42 has no non-negative solutions.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 8360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9da8fb1c04104fcc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] All solutions to LDE 1053x+481y=39**\n\nFind all solutions to 1053x+481y=39.",
			"x": 19000,
			"y": 8360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "eb726a2727db418f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Solve four LDEs**\n\nFor each of 221x+143y=13, 286x+121y=33, 1700x+867y=17, 1232x+553y=63: find (i) a single solution, (ii) all solutions, (iii) all non-negative solutions if they exist.",
			"x": 18610,
			"y": 8610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b70dc34cb5ff46b3",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 20340,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 2120,
			"height": 4160,
			"label": "Induction"
		},
		{
			"id": "74f1fa81250e4f02",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 20390,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 1240,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Mathematical Induction"
		},
		{
			"id": "f336300976154544",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Principle of Mathematical Induction**\n\nIf P(1) is true and P(k) ⟹ P(k+1) for all k, then P(n) is true for all n ∈ Z⁺. The domino principle: P(1) ⟹ P(2) ⟹ P(3) ⟹ ⋯. Two steps: base case (verify P(1)) and induction step (assume P(k), prove P(k+1)).",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ea1a4930738645e9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Induction example: inequality**\n\nWorked example: show 2n+2 ≤ 4n for all n ≥ 1. Base case: n=1 gives 4 ≤ 4. Induction step: assume 2k+2 ≤ 4k, show 2(k+1)+2 ≤ 4(k+1) by using 4(k+1) = 4k+4 ≥ (2k+2)+4.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "206cff854a9a4d79",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove 2n ≤ 2^n**\n\nShow that 2n ≤ 2^n for every n ∈ Z⁺, using mathematical induction.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "09dac4b30a9c44e0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Induction ↔ Well-Ordering Principle**\n\nProve that induction and the Well-Ordering Principle are logically equivalent: starting from WOP, prove induction; starting from induction, prove WOP.",
			"x": 21220,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "2f3d9c26a56145e2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Induction example: divisibility**\n\nWorked example: show 5|(6^k − 1) for all k ∈ Z⁺. Base case: 6^1 − 1 = 5. Induction step: write 6^{k+1} − 1 = (1+5)·6^k − 1 = 5·6^k + (6^k − 1), and both terms are divisible by 5.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "65d0d202d6b844f6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Bernoulli's Inequality**\n\nShow that for all x ≥ −1 and n ∈ Z⁺, (1+x)^n ≥ 1+nx. Induction on n, using (1+x)^{k+1} = (1+x)(1+x)^k ≥ (1+x)(1+kx).",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "8f501f2bc5214a86",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] nth root of 2 bound**\n\nShow that ²√[n]{2} ≤ 1 + 1/n for all n ∈ Z⁺. Equivalently, 2 ≤ (1+1/n)^n by induction (using Bernoulli's inequality or direct computation).",
			"x": 21220,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "7c611d6a81e04b94",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Induction example: L-tiling**\n\nA 2^n × 2^n chessboard with one tile removed can be L-tiled. Base case: 2×2 minus one square is an L-shape. Induction step: divide 2^{n+1} × 2^{n+1} board into four quadrants; place one L-tile at the center to reduce each quadrant to the 2^n × 2^n case. Shows induction works for geometric arguments.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "5dc4b86dac2c4bbb",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Domino tilings of a 2×n grid**\n\nDetermine the number of domino tilings of a 2×n grid and prove the formula. Hint: the count satisfies a Fibonacci-like recurrence f(n) = f(n−1) + f(n−2) with f(1)=1, f(2)=2.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "03882e6acce84b59",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 20390,
			"y": 1400,
			"width": 2020,
			"height": 590,
			"label": "Summation Notation"
		},
		{
			"id": "9586d68ebcf141d8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Sigma notation**\n\nThe expression Σ_{i=n}^{m} r_i means r_n + r_{n+1} + ⋯ + r_m. The variable i is the summation index, n and m are the bounds, and r_i is the summand. Essentially a for-loop. Introduces compact notation for sums that appear in many induction proofs.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 1490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "c1f28f5f0c89411c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Summation identity via induction**\n\nWorked example: prove Σ_{n=1}^{k} 1/(n(n+1)) = k/(k+1). Base case: 1/2 = 1/2. Induction step: peel off the (k+1)-th term and use the induction hypothesis to simplify. The key technique: separate the last term from the sum.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "0ece2eb9d3254f90",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Alternating sum of odd squares**\n\nFind an expression for Σ_{k=1}^{n} (−1)^k (2k−1)² and prove it by induction. First compute several values to guess the formula, then verify.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5dbf781f5b434ca8",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Sum 1+2+⋯+n**\n\nShow that Σ_{k=1}^{n} k = n(n+1)/2 for all n ∈ Z⁺ by induction.",
			"x": 21220,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "75ab978f3b084e85",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Odd-number pyramid row sums**\n\nOdd numbers arranged in a pyramid: row 1 is {1}, row 2 is {3,5}, row 3 is {7,9,11}, etc. Find a formula for the sum of the numbers on the nth row and prove it by induction. The answer is n³.",
			"x": 21610,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0e60eead897e4b9f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Sum of squares formula**\n\nShow that Σ_{n=1}^{k} n² = k(k+1)(2k+1)/6 by induction.",
			"x": 22000,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c1b255e24c354f3b",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 20390,
			"y": 2020,
			"width": 850,
			"height": 1030,
			"label": "Strong Induction"
		},
		{
			"id": "9f285947377c42a1",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Generalized induction**\n\nThe base case need not be n=1. To prove P(n) for all even numbers ≥ 10: base case P(10), step P(2n) ⟹ P(2n+2). This is equivalent to standard induction via the substitution Q(n) = P(2n). Any arithmetic progression can serve as the induction domain.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 2110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "a0583a50ced446e5",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Strong induction**\n\nIf P(1) is true and P(1)∧P(2)∧⋯∧P(k) ⟹ P(k+1) for all k, then P(n) holds for all n ∈ Z⁺. The induction hypothesis now assumes all previous cases, not just P(k).",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 2360,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "9b15aa5178664fef",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Strong induction equals regular induction**\n\nStrong and regular induction are logically equivalent. Proof: define Q(k) = P(1)∧⋯∧P(k). Regular induction on Q gives strong induction on P. Since regular induction uses a weaker hypothesis, (strong ⟹ regular) is immediate. Thus both forms prove exactly the same statements.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 2610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3d749d07dd184cdd",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Strong induction example: postage stamps**\n\nAny amount ≥ 8 cents can be formed using 3-cent and 5-cent stamps. Three base cases: 8=3+5, 9=3·3, 10=5·2. Induction step for n+1 > 10: write n+1 = (n−2)+3, apply the hypothesis to n−2 ≥ 8. Illustrates why multiple base cases are sometimes needed.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 2610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "fc2329694f7d433c",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Binary representation of positive integers**\n\nShow that every positive integer can be uniquely written as a sum of distinct powers of 2. Use strong induction: n is either even (divide by 2) or odd (subtract 1).",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "5bfae93459894045",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Marble game winning strategy**\n\nTwo bowls, each with marbles. Players alternate removing any positive number of marbles from one bowl. The player taking the last marble wins. Show that if both bowls start with the same number, the second player always has a winning strategy.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f244e63965454861",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 20390,
			"y": 3080,
			"width": 1240,
			"height": 1030,
			"label": "Recursion and Structural Induction"
		},
		{
			"id": "49b79ff3f477485e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Recursive definitions**\n\nA recursively defined set has a basis (initial elements) and a constructor (rule for building new elements from existing ones). Example: E with basis {0} and constructors c₁(x)=−x, c₂(x)=x+2 generates all even integers. Sequences can also be defined recursively.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 3170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "19ee60859f2b4d69",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The Fibonacci sequence**\n\nDefined by x₁=x₂=1 and x_n=x_{n−1}+x_{n−2}. Computes as 1,1,2,3,5,8,13,…. A sequence is not a set — order matters. Recursive objects need not have a natural linear ordering, which motivates a different type of induction.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 3420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "4888a2edf1904089",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Principle of structural induction**\n\nIf S is recursively defined with basis b₁,…,bₙ and constructor c, and P holds for all basis elements, and P(s₁)∧⋯∧P(sₖ) ⟹ P(c(s₁,…,sₖ)), then P(s) for all s ∈ S. Base case: check all basis elements. Constructor step: assume P for ingredients, show P for the result.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 3420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "68e4272f3a1e47c4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Structural induction example: divisibility**\n\nS is defined by: 3∈S, and if a,b∈S then a+b∈S. Show 3|s for all s∈S. Base case: 3|3. Constructor step: if 3|a and 3|b, then 3|(a+b). First full worked example of structural induction.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "536462b5bde9449a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Fibonacci closed form**\n\nLet x₁=x₂=1 and x_n = x_{n−1}+x_{n−2}. Define α_± = (1±√5)/2. Show that x_n = (α₊ⁿ − α₋ⁿ)/√5 using strong induction.",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "253f4193a7364098",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Closed form for a recursive sequence**\n\nGiven x₁=3, x₂=7, and x_k = 5x_{k−1} − 6x_{k−2}, show that x_k = 2^k + 3^{k−1} using strong induction.",
			"x": 21220,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "fef6b7b6bff94fb3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Balanced parentheses in logical formulas**\n\nLogical formulas are recursively defined: basis {T,F,R} and constructors (¬P), (P∧Q), (P∨Q), (P⟹Q), (P⟺Q). Show that any valid formula has an equal number of left and right parentheses, using structural induction.",
			"x": 20440,
			"y": 3920,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "94f675e3a09646c4",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Binary string reversal**\n\nFor finite binary strings s,t, prove that (st)^R = t^R s^R, where s^R denotes the reversal. Use induction on the length of t (or structural induction on the concatenation operation).",
			"x": 20830,
			"y": 3920,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4fd7eadea7594191",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Structural induction on pairs**\n\nLet S ⊆ Z*×Z* with (0,0) ∈ S and if (a,b) ∈ S then (a,b+1), (a+1,b+1), (a+2,b+1) ∈ S. Show a ≤ 2b for all (a,b) ∈ S using structural induction.",
			"x": 21220,
			"y": 3920,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3f1430dca8e44d33",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22560,
			"y": 0,
			"width": 2510,
			"height": 5970,
			"label": "Group Theory"
		},
		{
			"id": "776ad8c81d354260",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22610,
			"y": 90,
			"width": 2410,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Groups — First Principles"
		},
		{
			"id": "00ad624dc75b4c58",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Group definition**\n\nA group (G,·) is a set G with a binary operator satisfying: (1) associativity, (2) existence of an identity element e, (3) every element has an inverse. Notation: a^n for n-fold product, a^{−1} for inverse, a^0 = e.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "62a718ece9d44f02",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Abelian groups**\n\nA group is abelian if ab = ba for all a,b ∈ G. All groups seen so far (Z_n, Q*, Z, R) are abelian. The symmetric group S_X (for |X| ≥ 3) is not abelian — function composition does not commute in general.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "8cf23817808f49a0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Basic group properties**\n\nProposition: (1) the identity is unique, (2) ab=ac implies b=c (left cancellation, and similarly right), (3) the inverse of each element is unique, (4) (ab)^{−1} = b^{−1}a^{−1}. Proof of (3): if ar=e=as then r=s by cancellation.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "e37cabcceaf14297",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Q* is a group under multiplication**\n\nThe nonzero rationals Q* form a group under multiplication: associativity is inherited, 1 is the identity, and p/q has inverse q/p. The zero element must be excluded because 0 has no multiplicative inverse.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "cd4ee18bfcd14965",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Check four structures for group axioms**\n\nDetermine whether each is a group: (a) Z⁺ under exponentiation, (b) Z under a⊗b=a+b+ab, (c) Q\\{0} under a⊗b=a/b, (d) Rock-Paper-Scissors with winner as binary operator.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "06344ef8f5534370",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] (a^{−1})^n = (a^n)^{−1}**\n\nConvince yourself that (a^{−1})^n = (a^n)^{−1} in any group.",
			"x": 24220,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "60f8d82072224600",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Odd integers are not a group under addition**\n\nShow that the odd integers do not form a group under addition. Which axiom(s) fail?",
			"x": 24610,
			"y": 430,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "fb5294c7a67c454a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The symmetric group**\n\nS_X is the set of all bijections f:X→X under composition. Associativity: composition is associative. Identity: id(x)=x. Inverses: bijections are invertible. S_X is not abelian for |X| ≥ 3: σ∘τ ≠ τ∘σ for suitable transpositions.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "35df8df5a9dc454d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Abelian iff (ab)^{−1} = a^{−1}b^{−1}**\n\nShow that G is abelian if and only if (ab)^{−1} = a^{−1}b^{−1} for all a,b ∈ G. Compare with the general formula (ab)^{−1} = b^{−1}a^{−1}.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "befd0ab6f5bf414f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Finish the proof of basic group properties**\n\nProve the remaining parts of Proposition 13: (1) uniqueness of identity, (2) left/right cancellation, (4) (ab)^{−1} = b^{−1}a^{−1}.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "50c27d67bbe84907",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] (a₁⋯aₙ)^{−1} = aₙ^{−1}⋯a₁^{−1}**\n\nShow that (a₁a₂⋯aₙ)^{−1} = aₙ^{−1}aₙ₋₁^{−1}⋯a₁^{−1} for any a₁,…,aₙ ∈ G. The shoe-sock property generalized.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3a7e99d8050149b9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Why Q with zero fails**\n\nExplain what goes wrong if we try to make Q (including 0) into a group under multiplication. Which axiom fails?",
			"x": 24220,
			"y": 680,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "068c55f0ac0145b2",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] The dihedral group**\n\nD_n is the group of symmetries of a regular n-gon under composition. For D_3: 6 elements {e, r, r², s, sr, sr²} where r is 120° rotation and s is a reflection. Every element is a product of r and s. D_n is non-abelian: sr ≠ rs.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "0921649b9a174ca9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Z_n is a group under addition**\n\n(Z_n, +) is a group: associativity inherits from Z, [0] is the identity, and [−a] is the inverse of [a]. Worked verification of all three axioms. Additive notation: a+a+a = 3a instead of a^3.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "27b2c03c35e34655",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute cycle compositions in S_5**\n\nA cycle (a₁a₂⋯aₖ) maps a₁↦a₂↦⋯↦aₖ↦a₁. Composition is right-to-left. Compute in S_5: (a) (134)(23), (b) (12)(345)(15), (c) (145)(25)(12).",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d838b07e40b54914",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] S_n is abelian iff n ∈ {1,2}**\n\nShow that S_n is abelian if and only if n ∈ {1,2}.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 930,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "8992237dd46f4e52",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] srs = r^{−1} in D_n**\n\nShow that srs = r^{−1} in D_n for all n ≥ 3.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "4a1768d53ca44795",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |D_n| = 2n**\n\nD_3 has 6 elements. How many elements does D_n have in general? Justify your answer by counting rotations and reflections.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c503280c54614d4b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] sr ≠ rs in D_n**\n\nProve that sr ≠ rs in D_3. Then prove it for D_n with n ≥ 3 in general.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ff975653efcb4170",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] {[1]_6,[5]_6} is a group under multiplication mod 6**\n\nDetermine whether G = {[1]_6,[5]_6} is a group under multiplication modulo 6. Check all three group axioms.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 1180,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "47b187270bbd4a00",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22610,
			"y": 1400,
			"width": 2410,
			"height": 1090,
			"label": "Subgroups and Order"
		},
		{
			"id": "802895e890354c58",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Group order and element order**\n\nThe order of G is |G| (its cardinality). The order of g ∈ G is the smallest n ∈ Z⁺ with g^n = e, or ∞ if no such n exists. Examples: in Z_8* under multiplication, |[3]|=2. In D_3, |r|=3, |s|=2. In (Z,+), every nonzero element has infinite order.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 1490,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "3134997182404f97",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Order divides exponent**\n\nIf g has order n, then g^k = e if and only if n|k. Proof (⟸): g^k = (g^n)^s = e. Proof (⟹): write k=nq+r by Division Algorithm; g^r = e with 0 ≤ r < n forces r=0.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "f3a6e540929e42dc",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Subgroup definition**\n\nH ≤ G means H ⊆ G and (H,·) is itself a group under the same operation. The group operations must match: {[1]_6,[5]_6} under multiplication is a group but not a subgroup of (Z_6,+). Example: Z ≤ Q ≤ R under addition.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "28766352419f40e3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |ab| = |ba|**\n\nProve |ab| = |ba| for all a,b ∈ G. Hint: first show |aba^{−1}| = |b|, then conclude.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 1740,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c223b570af9841a3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Order of a power**\n\nIf g has order n, then |g^k| = n/gcd(n,k). This connects element order to the gcd — the order shrinks precisely by the common factor between k and n.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d20578cf36e14e56",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Subgroup test**\n\nIf H ⊆ G is nonempty and ab^{−1} ∈ H for all a,b ∈ H, then H ≤ G. Proof: (1) associativity inherited, (2) e = aa^{−1} ∈ H, (3) h^{−1} = eh^{−1} ∈ H. A one-condition shortcut.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "aa51e4fa8ca143a7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Alternative subgroup test**\n\nShow that if H ⊆ G is nonempty and (i) ab ∈ H for all a,b ∈ H and (ii) c^{−1} ∈ H for all c ∈ H, then H ≤ G.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b92cedfc2a114500",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Center Z(G) is a subgroup**\n\nDefine Z(G) = {a ∈ G : ab = ba for all b ∈ G}. Show Z(G) ≤ G.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "17b4cf0447c54f51",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Centralizer C(H) is a subgroup**\n\nIf H ≤ G, define C(H) = {g ∈ G : gh = hg for all h ∈ H}. Show C(H) ≤ G.",
			"x": 24220,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "29537167d71e48f5",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Order of disjoint cycle product**\n\nIf σ ∈ S_n is a product of disjoint cycles, prove that |σ| equals the least common multiple of the cycle lengths.",
			"x": 24610,
			"y": 1990,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c16c7da1a3c0412a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Subgroup test example: centralizer**\n\nWorked example: fix g ∈ G and let H = {h ∈ G : hgh^{−1} = g}. Show H ≤ G using the subgroup test. For a,b ∈ H: (ab^{−1})g(ab^{−1})^{−1} = a(b^{−1}gb)a^{−1} = aga^{−1} = g.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "1a03543f56d44b92",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove the order-of-a-power formula**\n\nIf g has order n, prove that |g^k| = n/gcd(n,k). A challenging proof that combines the Division Algorithm with gcd properties.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b85c7b9a57534610",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Square-identity elements form a subgroup**\n\nLet G be an abelian group and H = {h ∈ G : h² = e}. Show H ≤ G using the subgroup test. Where does abelianness matter?",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "15edf7e05fa04fe7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Units of Z_n form a group**\n\nA unit [a]_n ∈ Z_n has a multiplicative inverse [b]_n with [a][b]=[1]. (a) Show Z_n* is a group under multiplication mod n. (b) Write out the elements of Z_12*.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 2240,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "e44731b0974c4177",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22610,
			"y": 2520,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 780,
			"label": "Cyclic Groups"
		},
		{
			"id": "c37de2dbe278414e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cyclic groups**\n\nG is cyclic if G = {g^n : n ∈ Z} for some generator g, written G = ⟨g⟩. Example: Z_4 = ⟨[1]_4⟩ = ⟨[3]_4⟩, but ⟨[2]_4⟩ = {[0],[2]} is a proper subgroup. A group may have multiple generators.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 2610,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "30515aa1ffab49c9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Cyclic subgroup is a subgroup**\n\nFor any g ∈ G, ⟨g⟩ ≤ G. Proof via subgroup test: if a=g^k and b=g^ℓ then ab^{−1}=g^{k−ℓ} ∈ ⟨g⟩.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "1051bb1f35d04231",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Cyclic implies abelian**\n\nShow that every cyclic group is abelian. If G = ⟨g⟩, then any two elements are g^k and g^ℓ, so their product is g^{k+ℓ} = g^{ℓ+k}.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "c03e716aaa214555",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Z is cyclic; describe ⟨n⟩**\n\nIs Z cyclic under addition? Describe the cyclic subgroup ⟨2⟩. Generalize to ⟨n⟩ for any nonzero integer n.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "9231a5d0885140c9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Z_8* not cyclic, Z_10* cyclic**\n\nShow that Z_8* is not cyclic, but Z_10* is cyclic. Find a generator for Z_10*.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 2860,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "144b79fee47d452b",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] |⟨g⟩| = |g|**\n\nIf g ∈ G has order n, show that |⟨g⟩| = |g| = n. The cyclic subgroup generated by g has exactly as many elements as the order of g.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "13d7faac005b4c1f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Element order divides cyclic group order**\n\nIf G is a cyclic group of order n, show that |a| divides n for every a ∈ G.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ba73435da3f54805",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] ⟨a^k⟩ = ⟨a^{gcd(k,n)}⟩**\n\nLet G be a group, a ∈ G with |a| = n, and k ∈ Z⁺. Show that ⟨a^k⟩ = ⟨a^{gcd(k,n)}⟩.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ca961c739f2a4e0e",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Every subgroup of a cyclic group is cyclic**\n\nShow that every subgroup of a cyclic group is cyclic. Hint: use the Division Algorithm on the smallest positive exponent in the subgroup.",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 3110,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ab940ab2e2ef4258",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22610,
			"y": 3330,
			"width": 1630,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Homomorphisms"
		},
		{
			"id": "aa9fb6215a04499f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Group homomorphism**\n\nA function φ: G → H between groups is a homomorphism if φ(x·y) = φ(x)⋆φ(y). The function respects the group structure — it translates the operation in G to the operation in H.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 3420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "193d20e8aa6447f0",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Well-definedness of homomorphisms**\n\nWhen a homomorphism is defined on equivalence classes (like Z_n), we must verify well-definedness: if [a]=[b] then φ([a])=φ([b]). Worked example: φ([x]_6) = [2x]_12 is well-defined, but ζ([x]_6) = [3x]_12 is not.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "cfb7f18139464bb9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Kernel and image**\n\nFor φ: G → H, the kernel ker(φ) = {g ∈ G : φ(g) = e_H} and the image im(φ) = {φ(g) : g ∈ G}. The kernel measures how far φ is from being injective; the image measures how far from being surjective.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "ec8b6bc97623442a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Check five maps for homomorphism**\n\nDetermine whether each is a group homomorphism: (a) φ(x)=x² on R*, (b) ψ([n])=[n+1] on Z_4, (c) χ(n)=r^n from Z to D_4, (d) β(σ)=number of fixed points from S_3 to Z_3, (e) γ(σ)=(12)σ on S_3.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 3670,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "1d247175694847ad",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Kernel and image example**\n\nWorked example: φ: Z_12 → Z_6, φ([x]_12) = [2x]_6. Computing all 12 outputs: ker(φ) = {[0],[3],[6],[9]} and im(φ) = {[0],[2],[4]}.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 3920,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "efe5e7f32b8840ea",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Properties of homomorphisms**\n\nNine properties: (1) φ(e_G)=e_H, (2) φ(g^n)=φ(g)^n, (3) |φ(g)| divides |g|, (4) ker ≤ G and im ≤ H, (5) φ(K) ≤ H for K ≤ G, (6) φ preserves cyclic subgroups, (7) φ preserves abelian subgroups, (8) φ^{−1}(L) ≤ G for L ≤ H, (9) φ injective iff ker = {e}.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 4170,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "50db42f13f8b4797",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Compute kernels of homomorphisms**\n\nDetermine and prove the kernel for: (a) δ(n)=[2n]_6 from Z to Z_6, (b) ρ([n]_12)=[n]_4, (c) τ: D_4 → Z_2 mapping rotations to 0 and reflections to 1.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "efc25494fdd848b9",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Inversion is a homomorphism iff abelian**\n\nShow that the map φ: G → G defined by φ(g) = g^{−1} is a homomorphism if and only if G is abelian.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "0af89f46a69e441f",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove homomorphism properties**\n\nProve the remaining properties from Proposition 5: φ(e)=e, φ(g^n)=φ(g)^n, |φ(g)| divides |g|, ker ≤ G, im ≤ H, φ preserves cyclic/abelian subgroups, φ^{−1}(L) ≤ G, φ injective iff ker = {e}.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "f562c6ab7e394e20",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Trivial kernel implies G ≅ φ(G)**\n\nIf φ: G → K is a homomorphism with ker(φ) = {e_G}, show that G ≅ φ(G).",
			"x": 23830,
			"y": 4420,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "89cfb83db966407b",
			"type": "group",
			"x": 22610,
			"y": 4640,
			"width": 1240,
			"height": 1280,
			"label": "Isomorphisms"
		},
		{
			"id": "fe56e33d364646e7",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Isomorphism definition**\n\nA group homomorphism φ: G → H that is also a bijection is an isomorphism. If one exists, G ≅ H — the groups are \"the same\" up to relabelling. Two groups are isomorphic iff their Cayley tables match after renaming elements.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 4730,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2670f8113a6c4e93",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Isomorphism example: three groups of order 2**\n\nZ_2, U={[1]_6,[5]_6}, and ⟨[2]_4⟩ all have the same Cayley table. Worked proof: define φ: Z_2 → U by φ([0])=[1]_6, φ([1])=[5]_6, verify it is a bijective homomorphism.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 4980,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "2281174b0a244131",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Isomorphic is an equivalence relation**\n\nShow that being isomorphic is an equivalence relation on the class of groups: reflexive (id), symmetric (φ^{−1}), transitive (φ∘ψ).",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 4980,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "b6f61ba6dc2443b3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Properties of isomorphisms**\n\nIf G ≅ H via φ: (1) φ^{−1} is an isomorphism, (2) G abelian iff H abelian, (3) G cyclic iff H cyclic, (4) φ(K) ≅ K for K ≤ G, (5) |g| = |φ(g)|, (6) |G| = |H|. Proof of (2): use bijectivity to lift commutativity between groups.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 5230,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "d95ad06f62294ec3",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Complete the isomorphism ψ: Z_2 → ⟨[2]_4⟩**\n\nComplete Example 9 by showing that ψ: Z_2 → ⟨[2]_4⟩ is an isomorphism.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 5230,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "d7ffe01fd4c84eca",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] ⟨r⟩ ≅ Z_3 in D_3**\n\nShow that the rotation subgroup ⟨r⟩ of D_3 is isomorphic to Z_3.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 5230,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "ce82ee0ee0cc4203",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[BIT] Classification of cyclic groups**\n\nEvery cyclic group is isomorphic to Z or Z_n: if |G|=∞ then G ≅ Z; if |G|=n then G ≅ Z_n. Proof (infinite case): map φ(k)=g^k, show it is a bijective homomorphism using triviality of the kernel.",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 5480,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 200
		},
		{
			"id": "25b1af82b33e49c5",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Aut(G) is a group**\n\nAn automorphism is an isomorphism G → G. Show that the set Aut(G) of all automorphisms of G forms a group under function composition.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 5480,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "3bca8ff5c58c484a",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] R and Q are not isomorphic**\n\nShow that (R,+) and (Q,+) are not isomorphic. Hint: consider the equation x+x=a and the surjectivity of the division-by-2 map.",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 5480,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "553c9e971ec941b6",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Conjugation and inner automorphisms**\n\n(a) Show c_g(h)=ghg^{−1} is an automorphism for all g. (b) Show Inn(G)={c_g : g ∈ G} is a group under composition. (c) Conclude Inn(G) ≤ Aut(G).",
			"x": 22660,
			"y": 5730,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "94e7b07133b849ad",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] Prove finite cyclic classification**\n\nProve Theorem 13(2): if G is a finite cyclic group of order n, then G ≅ Z_n.",
			"x": 23050,
			"y": 5730,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		},
		{
			"id": "71cb9995efab405d",
			"type": "text",
			"text": "**[EXERCISE] φ_q(r) = qr is an automorphism of Q**\n\nFor any nonzero q ∈ Q, show that φ_q: Q → Q defined by φ_q(r) = qr is an automorphism of (Q,+).",
			"x": 23440,
			"y": 5730,
			"width": 360,
			"height": 140,
			"color": "3"
		}
	],
	"edges": [
		{
			"id": "0d079b7d35794339",
			"fromNode": "ac4345faddf84091",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "9e7d9f88520940a4",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "What are these labeled blocks in a math textbook?"
		},
		{
			"id": "8b2f34aa16fd468c",
			"fromNode": "9e7d9f88520940a4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "3f17157092064ba4",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "Why can't I just use my intuition for what a word means?"
		},
		{
			"id": "e3aff64fb7e34452",
			"fromNode": "9e7d9f88520940a4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "42e6a4e678964fc4",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "What should I do right after I read a new definition?"
		},
		{
			"id": "47cbd974596d464c",
			"fromNode": "9e7d9f88520940a4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "6b6a5a4b5f54495e",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "Once we have definitions, what do we do with them?"
		},
		{
			"id": "8a09bc47864e4e24",
			"fromNode": "3f17157092064ba4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "2b62834657c54c66",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "What can I say about quirky numbers using only the definition?"
		},
		{
			"id": "e56167c0c1a54b7d",
			"fromNode": "3f17157092064ba4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "969b9834ce734817",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "How do mathematicians organize the objects they define?"
		},
		{
			"id": "222f65bc14d94c20",
			"fromNode": "42e6a4e678964fc4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "7d2b2ebf18574f47",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "Can I write my own precise definition?"
		},
		{
			"id": "1a0827b3a931488e",
			"fromNode": "42e6a4e678964fc4",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "5de20ea583114ae9",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "Can I generate examples for a definition I haven't seen before?"
		},
		{
			"id": "8164f42bbb5242ed",
			"fromNode": "6b6a5a4b5f54495e",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "1e9d42ee26c84fe9",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "How reliable are these results?"
		},
		{
			"id": "4200cd0c14ee4efc",
			"fromNode": "6b6a5a4b5f54495e",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "f179ab9c2588427f",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "How do I use a theorem — can I always apply it?"
		},
		{
			"id": "0d976d132d0345dd",
			"fromNode": "1e9d42ee26c84fe9",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "a7b594276c0a4149",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "How can anything be absolutely certain?"
		},
		{
			"id": "d252a50d776c48e9",
			"fromNode": "f179ab9c2588427f",
			"fromSide": "right",
			"toNode": "16812c4caed242ad",
			"toSide": "left",
			"label": "Can I identify hypothesis and conclusion in practice?"
		},
		{
			"id": "9c3a235d88114e8f",
			"fromNode": "f179ab9c2588427f",
			"fromSide": "right",
